<div id="review_4110164" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4110164" />
    <a title="Ann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/215009-ann"><img alt="Ann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1237148494p2/215009.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4110164?book_show_action=true">Aug 05, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann" href="/user/show/215009-ann">Ann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780345389961" href="/book/show/765614.A_Son_of_the_Circus">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4110164" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12745098672555959582">Critics may complain about the repetitive images of John Irving&apos;s books, but I love how he weaves the symbolism and influences of his life into his work. A Son of the Circus includes the common imagery of India, Toronto, central Europe, dwarfism, circuses, etc. from his other works. (More on that topic here: [<a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://www.readertravels.com/2006/09/India-via-the-John-Irving-Highway.php'>http://www.readertravels.com/2006/09/...</a>])<br/><br/>As always, I love his writing voice and the flow of the story. In this one, his nod to Graham Green is also a fun aspect of the story, a tribute to</span>
  <span id="freeText12745098672555959582" style="display:none">Critics may complain about the repetitive images of John Irving's books, but I love how he weaves the symbolism and influences of his life into his work. A Son of the Circus includes the common imagery of India, Toronto, central Europe, dwarfism, circuses, etc. from his other works. (More on that topic here: [<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.readertravels.com/2006/09/India-via-the-John-Irving-Highway.php">http://www.readertravels.com/2006/09/...</a>])<br /><br />As always, I love his writing voice and the flow of the story. In this one, his nod to Graham Green is also a fun aspect of the story, a tribute to one of his major influences. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12745098672555959582" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


